  "prompt": "How and when did Dhoni start his career?",
  "response": "Mahendra Singh Dhoni, commonly known as MS Dhoni, began his cricket career in the early 2000s after showcasing his talent in domestic cricket. Here's a timeline of how his career started:\n\n1. **Early Life and Domestic Career**  \n   - Dhoni was born on July 7, 1981, in Ranchi, Jharkhand (then part of Bihar).  \n   - He initially gained attention while playing for Bihar (later Jharkhand) in the Ranji Trophy, India's premier domestic cricket tournament.  \n   - His explosive batting and sharp wicketkeeping skills made him a standout player in domestic cricket.\n\n2. **First-Class Debut (1999)**  \n   - Dhoni made his first-class debut for Bihar in the 1999\u20132000 season.  \n   - Over the next few years, he continued to impress with his consistency and aggressive style of play.\n\n3. **India A Call-Up (2004)**  \n   - Dhoni\u2019s breakthrough came in 2004 when he was selected to play for India A against Kenya and Pakistan A.  \n   - His performances in these matches, including a blistering 120 against Pakistan A, caught the attention of national selectors.\n\n4. **International Debut (December 2004)**  \n   - Dhoni made his international debut for India in a One Day International (ODI) against Bangladesh on December 23, 2004.  \n   - He had a slow start initially but soon proved his worth with his aggressive batting and calm demeanor.\n\n5. **Rise to Fame**  \n   - Dhoni rose to prominence after his match-winning innings of 148 against Pakistan in 2005 and a record-breaking 183* against Sri Lanka later that year.  \n   - His ability to finish games under pressure earned him the nickname \"Captain Cool.\"\n\n6. **Captaincy and Legacy**  \n   - Dhoni was appointed captain of the Indian cricket team in 2007.  \n   - Under his leadership, India won the inaugural ICC T20 World Cup (2007), the ICC Cricket World Cup (2011), and the ICC Champions Trophy (2013).  \n\nDhoni\u2019s journey from a small-town boy to one of India\u2019s most successful cricket captains is an inspiring story of dedication, hard work, and perseverance. He retired from international cricket on **August 15, 2020**, but continues to play in the Indian Premier League (IPL) for the Chennai Super Kings (CSK).",
  "temperature": 1.0,
